ciety; Yale; FindAGrave)","body":"Served as Rhode Island State Treasurer 1938-1940; ran as Republican nominee for US Senate 1948 (lost to Theodore F. Green). The 1948 race was the high-water mark of his political career after South Kingstown Town Council, RI State Senate, and an unsuccessful 1932 US House run.","number":1},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Food distributor to liberated Europe, 1944-45","body":"As Liaison Officer to the Chief Quartermaster of the U.S. Army based in England from February 1944, he played a major role in food distribution to liberated northwestern Europe. Discharged Lt. Colonel November 1945 after Tunisia, Palermo, and Naples Civil Affairs assignments."},{"number":3,"category":"scholarship","header":"Wrote a 1949 book on civil affairs reconstruction","body":"Published 'Civil Affairs: An Experiment in Reconstruction' (1949) based on his WWII Liaison Officer experience. Also co-authored a 1951 American Fisheries Society paper on modification of the sexual cycle in brook trout — his family's American Fish Culture Company connection."},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"Cavalry on the Mexican border, 1916","body":"He enlisted Troop D 1st NY Cavalry as a private in October 1915 at twenty-three; called to active duty for the Mexican border intervention June 1916; commissioned 2nd Lt. then promoted 1st Lt. in the 14th U.S. Cavalry at Del Rio TX. Discharged February 1919 — never went overseas in WWI."}],"number_of_marriages":1,"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Thomas Pierrepont Hazard","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Hazard","middle_name":"Pierrepont","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1915"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST022","dates":"1915","notes":" — Wolf's Head Senior Society. Psi Upsilon Frate